the Beautiful Blond.

00:00:52.484 --> 00:00:55.422
The blond ale is often
referred to as the gateway beer

00:00:55.422 --> 00:00:59.092
to craft beer because it is
the lightest of the styles.

00:00:59.092 --> 00:01:01.470
It has virtually no hop presence in it.

00:01:01.470 --> 00:01:04.221
Um, the malts are very neutral as well,

00:01:04.221 --> 00:01:06.266
they're mostly pale malt
with a little bit of biscuit,

00:01:06.266 --> 00:01:08.185
so you don't have a
lot of caramel flavors,

00:01:08.185 --> 00:01:10.479
you don't have a lot of
dark, roast-y flavors.

00:01:10.479 --> 00:01:12.272
Across the board it's very clean,

00:01:12.272 --> 00:01:14.399
it's very easy and approachable.

00:01:14.399 --> 00:01:16.733
It's a great summertime drink,
especially by the beach,

00:01:16.733 --> 00:01:18.195
so a lot of the lighter blonde ales

00:01:18.195 --> 00:01:21.058
are made in cans as well.

00:01:21.058 --> 00:01:24.016
I used this because we
really wanted to showcase the

00:01:24.016 --> 00:01:26.369
strawberries, so we didn't
want to interfere with it.

00:01:26.369 --> 00:01:29.673
But typical in a mojito,
is to use soda water.

00:01:29.673 --> 00:01:31.712
So anywhere you can use soda water,

00:01:31.712 --> 00:01:33.710
in my book, you can use beer.

00:01:33.710 --> 00:01:35.226
And so I needed to use one of the most

00:01:35.226 --> 00:01:38.423
neutral styles of beer,
but still give it a little

00:01:38.423 --> 00:01:42.475
bit of flavor, and so I
chose the Beautiful Blonde.

00:01:42.475 --> 00:01:45.013
