to have fruit flavors

00:01:53.801 --> 00:01:55.474
or are they pretty...

00:01:55.474 --> 00:01:57.567
- It's not characteristic to have

00:01:57.567 --> 00:01:59.319
fruit flavors in this beer.

00:01:59.319 --> 00:02:02.783
Fruit flavors, often times
in beer, come from the yeast.

00:02:02.783 --> 00:02:03.865
And the yeast used in this,

00:02:03.865 --> 00:02:05.713
'cause it's an American-style...

00:02:05.713 --> 00:02:07.494
Americans pretty much
invented the American

00:02:07.494 --> 00:02:10.497
blonde ale, well, obviously.

00:02:10.497 --> 00:02:13.124
But the yeast strands used in this are

00:02:13.124 --> 00:02:14.751
American yeast strands
which typically aren't

00:02:14.751 --> 00:02:16.837
very fruity, and you wouldn't find any

00:02:16.837 --> 00:02:18.171
fruit from any of the malts.

00:02:18.171 --> 00:02:20.048
So, you're gonna find a
little bit of biscuit flavor,

00:02:20.048 --> 00:02:22.008
which will be nice to go
with the strawberries,

00:02:22.008 --> 00:02:25.345
maybe a little strawberry
shortcake with mint on top.

00:02:25.345 --> 00:02:27.559
- Can you talk a little
bit about when you're

00:02:27.559 --> 00:02:31.956
concocting a recipe for
this, you can have either,

00:02:31.956 --> 00:02:34.145
you know, sort of, inspiration
from the culinary world

00:02:34.145 --> 00:02:35.772
whether it's, like, basil or strawberry

00:02:35.772 --> 00:02:37.399
or even some other dish,

00:02:37.399 --> 00:02:39.576
or you can start with the beer.

00:02:39.576 --> 00:02:41.101
If someone starts with
the beer, how do you

00:02:41.101 --> 00:02:43.113
work towards building out a cocktail?

00:02:43.113 --> 00:02:44.947
What's your sort of process for that?

00:02:44.947 --> 00:02:46.992
- Well, I would, if you
have a favorite style,

00:02:46.992 --> 00:02:49.995
I would break down the
key flavor characteristics

00:02:49.995 --> 00:02:53.915
of that and, for example,
we'll use a stout.

00:02:53.915 --> 00:02:56.582
You know, we've got
chocolate, we've got coffee.

00:02:56.582 --> 00:02:59.504
Is it lighter in body,
or is it heavier in body?

00:02:59.504 --> 00:03:01.256
All these things that
you have to think about.

00:03:01.256 --> 00:03:04.050
And then, you take those
flavors and you think about

00:03:04.050 --> 00:03:07.262
what spirits might play well with that?

00:03:07.262 --> 00:03:09.708
I have chocolate and I have espresso,

00:03:09.708 --> 00:03:12.893
typically you go towards
barrel aged spirits,

00:03:12.893 --> 00:03:17.230
such as whiskey, bourbon, the darker rums.

00:03:17.722 --> 00:03:18.768
Then you start figuring out,

00:03:18.768 --> 00:03:20.792
well I like the caramelized
flavors and the vanilla

00:03:20.792 --> 00:03:24.774
flavors in the barrel that
play very well with the

00:03:24.774 --> 00:03:27.447
chocolate and espresso and the stout.

00:03:27.447 --> 00:03:29.657
And then from there you
can just throw in other

00:03:29.657 --> 00:03:32.471
ingredients, sometimes,
orange goes really nicely

00:03:32.471 --> 00:03:34.167
with both, 'cause orange and chocolate.

00:03:34.167 --> 00:03:35.916
Fruit and chocolate and bourbon.

00:03:35.916 --> 00:03:37.208
You know, so it's just, kind of,

00:03:37.208 --> 00:03:39.107
going through in your head,

00:03:39.107 --> 00:03:41.907
wherever you start you
can build off of it.

